<div class="markdown"><h2>Generating fake data</h2>
<p>The problem of interest is to look at mortality rates, which are given in terms of exposures &#40;whether or not a life experienced a death in a given year&#41;.</p>
<p>We&#39;ll grab some example rates from an insurance table, which has a &quot;selection&quot; component: When someone enters observation, say at age 50, their mortality is path dependent &#40;so for someone who started being observed at 50 will have a different risk/mortality rate at age 55 than someone who started being observed at 45&#41;.</p>
<p>Addtionally, there may be additional groups of interest, such as:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>high/medium/low risk classification</p>
</li>
<li><p>sex</p>
</li>
<li><p>group &#40;e.g. company, data source, etc.&#41;</p>
</li>
<li><p>type of insurance product offered</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>The example data will start with only the risk classification above</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='julia hljs pluto-input'>function generate_data_individual(tbl,issue_age=rand(50:55),inforce_years=rand(1:30),risklevel=rand(1:3))
    # risk_factors will scale the "true" parameter up or down
    # we observe the assigned risklevel, but not risk_factor
    risk_factors = [0.7,1.0,1.5]
    rf = risk_factors[risklevel]
    deaths = rand(inforce_years) .&lt; (tbl.select[issue_age][issue_age .+ inforce_years .- 1 ] .* rf)
    
    endpoint = if sum(deaths) == 0
        last(inforce_years)
    else
        findfirst(deaths)
    end
    id= uuid1()
    map(1:endpoint) do i
        (
        issue_age=issue_age,
        risklevel = risklevel,
        att_age = issue_age + i -1,
        death = deaths[i],
        id = id,
    )
    end
    
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-generate_data_individual' class='pluto-output'>generate_data_individual (generic function with 4 methods)</pre>

<div class="markdown"><h2>1: A single binomial parameter model</h2>
<p>Estiamte <span class="tex">$p$</span>, the average mortality rate, not accounting for any variation within the population/sample:</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='julia hljs pluto-input'>@model function mortality(data,deaths) 
    p ~ Beta(1,1)
    for i = 1:nrow(data)
        deaths[i] ~ Binomial(data.exposures[i],p)
    end
end</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><h3>Plotting samples from the posterior</h3>
<p>We can see that the sampling of possible posterior parameters doesn&#39;t really fit the data very well since our model was so simplified. The lines represent the posterior binomial probability.</p>
<p>This is saying that for the observed data, if there really is just a single probability <code>p</code> that governs the true process that came up with the data, there&#39;s a pretty narrow range of values it could possibly be:</p>
</div>

<div class="markdown"><h2>2. Parametric model</h2>
<p>In this example, we utilize a <a href="https://juliaactuary.github.io/MortalityTables.jl/stable/ParametricMortalityModels/#MortalityTables.MakehamBeard">MakehamBeard</a> parameterization because it&#39;s already very similar in form to a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_function">logistic function</a>. This is important because our desired output is a probability &#40;ie the probablity of a death at a given age&#41;, so the value must be constrained to be in the interval between zero and one.</p>
<p>The <strong>prior</strong> values for <code>a</code>,<code>b</code>,<code>c</code>, and <code>k</code> are chosen to constrain the hazard &#40;mortality&#41; rate to be between zero and one. </p>
<p>This isn&#39;t an ideal parameterization &#40;e.g. we aren&#39;t including information about the select underwriting period&#41;, but is an example of utilizing Bayesian techniques on life experience data.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='julia hljs pluto-input'>@model function mortality2(data,deaths) 
    a ~ Exponential(0.1)
    b ~ Exponential(0.1)
    c = 0.
    k ~ truncated(Exponential(1),1,Inf)
    
    # use the variables to create a parametric mortality model
    m = MortalityTables.MakehamBeard(;a,b,c,k)

    # loop through the rows of the dataframe to let Turing observe the data 
    # and how consistent the parameters are with the data
    for i = 1:nrow(data)
        age = data.att_age[i]	
        q = MortalityTables.hazard(m,age)
        deaths[i] ~ Binomial(data.exposures[i],q)
    end
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-mortality2' class='pluto-output'>mortality2 (generic function with 2 methods)</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p>We combine the model with the data:</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='julia hljs pluto-input'>m2 = mortality2(data,data.deaths)</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><h2>3. Parametric model</h2>
<p>This model extends the prior to create a multi-level model. Each risk class &#40;<code>risklevel</code>&#41; gets its own <span class="tex">$a$</span> paramater in the <code>MakhamBeard</code> model. The prior for <span class="tex">$a_i$</span> is determined by the hyperparameter <span class="tex">$\bar&#123;a&#125;$</span>.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='julia hljs pluto-input'>@model function mortality3(data,deaths) 
    risk_levels = length(levels(data.risklevel))
    b ~ Exponential(0.1)
    ā ~ Exponential(0.1)
    a ~ filldist(Exponential(ā), risk_levels)
    c = 0
    k ~ truncated(Exponential(1),1,Inf)
    
    # use the variables to create a parametric mortality model

    # loop through the rows of the dataframe to let Turing observe the data 
    # and how consistent the parameters are with the data
    for i = 1:nrow(data)
        risk = data.risklevel[i]
        
        m = MortalityTables.MakehamBeard(;a=a[risk],b,c,k)
        age = data.att_age[i]	
        q = MortalityTables.hazard(m,age)
        deaths[i] ~ Binomial(data.exposures[i],q)
    end
end</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><h2>Handling non-unit exposures</h2>
<p>The key is to use the Poisson distribution:</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='julia hljs pluto-input'>@model function mortality4(data,deaths) 
    risk_levels = length(levels(data.risklevel))
    b ~ Exponential(0.1)
    ā ~ Exponential(0.1)
    a ~ filldist(Exponential(ā), risk_levels)
    c ~ Beta(4,18)
    k ~ truncated(Exponential(1),1,Inf)
    
    # use the variables to create a parametric mortality model

    # loop through the rows of the dataframe to let Turing observe the data 
    # and how consistent the parameters are with the data
    for i = 1:nrow(data)
        risk = data.risklevel[i]
        
        m = MortalityTables.MakehamBeard(;a=a[risk],b,c,k)
        age = data.att_age[i]	
        q = MortalityTables.hazard(m,age)
        deaths[i] ~ Poisson(data.exposures[i] * q)
    end
end</code></pre>

    data_weight = data.exposures ./ sum(data.exposures)
    data_weight = .√(data_weight ./ maximum(data_weight) .* 20)
    color_i = data.risklevel
    
    p = scatter(
        data.att_age,
        data.fraction, 
        markersize = data_weight, 
        alpha = 0.5, 
        color=color_i,
        label = "Experience data point (size indicates relative exposure quantity)",
        xlabel="age",
        ylim=(0.0,0.25),
        ylabel="mortality rate", 
        title="Parametric Bayseian Mortality"
    )
    

    # show n samples from the posterior plotted on the graph
    n = 100
    
    ages = sort!(unique(data.att_age))
    for r in 1:3	
        for i in 1:n
            s = sample(chain4,1)
            a = only(s[Symbol("a[$r]")])
            b = only(s[:b])
            k = only(s[:k])
            c = 0
            m = MortalityTables.MakehamBeard(;a,b,c,k)
            if i == 1 
                plot!(ages,age -&gt; MortalityTables.hazard(m,age),label="risk level $r", alpha = 0.2,color=r)
            else
                plot!(ages,age -&gt; MortalityTables.hazard(m,age),label="", alpha = 0.2,color=r)
            end
        end
    end
    p
end</code></pre>
